I think the issue is, if the timer handler (TimerEventHandler()) is queued, there is a time gap between we queue it and it gets called, during this gap, there's a possibility that a call to timer_Handler() has not finished (to be precise, the timer has not been poped from the timer list) and the next timer expire event is queued. When this happen to the last time expiry event, specifically, when timer_Handler() is in processing the last time expiry event (say A), a new timer expiry event (say B) is queued, and later when starting to handle the latter timer  event B, the active timer list is already empty, which will trigger this issue.

So, I think there are two possible solutions:
1. Keep line 303, which requires no change for this patch.
2. Change the TimerEventHandler() to the following:
static void TimerEventHandler(void* param1Ptr, void* param2Ptr)
{
    LE_UNUSED(param1Ptr);
    LE_UNUSED(param2Ptr);
    timer_ThreadRec_t *timerRecPtr = thread_GetTimerRecPtr(TIMER_NON_WAKEUP);

    if (le_dls_NumLinks(&timerRecPtr->activeTimerList) > 0)
    {
        timer_Handler(timerRecPtr);
    }
}

Tested both worked.

